I have in the past maintained, and I still maintain that there has never
been a second generation UNIX system.  The closest approach ever made to
this goal was the Univeristy of New South Wales code, and even then, that
effort was significantly lacking in release engineering.  As such, there
has never been a serious, professional attempt at producing a desktop
UNIX.

The complexity that sets a system adminisrtator apart from a user is
management of system meta-state information that is generally never
seen by a user operating in their defined work space.  This can be
roughly divided between the concepts of "software installation" and
"management of access controls".

In both cases, the "pinacle of achievement", Windows NT, fails in the
same way.

A general user has no need for this information, and thus no interest
in becoming educated.  The do not care *how* something works, they care
*that* it works.

Because of this, service consumers and service providers are seperate
classes.  A system administrator is a user of the service provider
system.

The majority of "Unix System Administration Horror Stories" are related
either to people running with more priviledges than they should be to
accomplish the task at hand, or people being less educated than they
should be to accomplish the task at hand.  You don't go to a GP for
heart surgery.

Despite the overwhelming desire to promote uneducated users to the post
of system administrator based on seniority rather than technical merit,
the task requires an educated system administrator, not a glorified
user.  Even NetWare and NT are fragile in this regard (ever heard of a
CNE?).


If a system administrator, who by virtue of his position is expected to
be sufficiently educated to operate at low risk in a fragile environment,
screws up, it is either the finite (but low) risk causing the problem,
or the administrator is, indeed, an idiot.

UNIX could *not* have prevented the problem in most cases (those that it
could are admitted deficiencies which I will not argue for -- you have
yet to cite one, and far be it for me to thus arm you).  What *could*
have prevented the problem is apropriate hiring practices and pay scales
to ensure the person in the administrator position would not exagerate
the risk inherent in being "God" over the machine.

Either way, the problem is one of human error.

